Specializing in technology transactions, David combines deep legal and technical expertise with extensive experience structuring and negotiating complex agreements to deliver practical, trusted advice and successful client outcomes.
David is a partner in the firm’s Technology Law and Cyber/Data groups. His practice focuses primarily on complex commercial transactions, in particular those involving technology or outsourcing, such as high-stakes enterprise IT systems and digital transformation projects.
For over 20 years, David has advised private‑ and public‑sector clients across a wide range of industries on complex and strategic technology‑related transactions, including technology procurement, business process (BPO) and informational technology (ITO) outsourcings, IT systems development, integration and implementation projects, inbound and outbound software and other technology licensing, cloud (SaaS, IaaS, PaaS) services agreements, telecommunications services agreements, supply agreements, data sharing arrangements, joint venture and other strategic alliance arrangements, mergers and acquisitions, and financings. With a deep understanding of not only the legal issues, but also the business and technological issues that arise from both established and emerging technologies, he brings a practical, solution-oriented approach that balances legal risk with business opportunity to get deals done efficiently and effectively. Further, David draws on deep experience and a broad industry network to deliver current, informed insight into market terms, regulatory developments, and specific technology vendor dynamics.
In addition, David advises on technology and data commercialization, intellectual property, e-commerce, privacy and data protection, cybersecurity, procurement (including under RFPs, NRFPs and JSRFPs), open source software, blockchain, artificial intelligence (including governance and contracting), quantum computing, social and other digital media and anti-spam regulation.
David has extensive experience representing public-sector clients, including governments, government departments/agencies and Crown corporations. He has a deep understanding of the legal, policy, and trade agreement compliance requirements that uniquely shape public-sector procurement in Canada. David has advised on some of the largest and most high-profile technology-related projects for the British Columbia public sector over the past 20 years.
Earlier in his career, David served as in‑house counsel to a TSX‑listed international technology product development company. Working closely with executive leadership and engineering teams, he developed a practical understanding of how to manage legal risk and cost, ensure regulatory compliance, and scale revenue through efficient deal negotiation and contracting. This experience continues to inform David’s pragmatic approach to delivering commercially aligned, results-focused legal advice.

#### Select Recent Experience
Some of his recent notable work includes acting for:
- a multi-national energy and fuel distribution company on a transformative, AI‑driven IT operations outsourcing implemented across more than 20 countries;
- the Government of British Columbia on the procurement under a negotiated RFP (NRFP) of next‑generation managed workplace technology services supporting laptops and other end‑user devices for government and select broader public‑sector personnel across British Columbia;
- a multinational energy company on a large and complex enterprise resource planning (ERP) system integration project involving multiple ERP software vendors and system integration service providers;
- a UK-based cloud-native digital banking platform provider with respect to the negotiation of a SaaS agreement with its first customer in North America, a Canadian bank;
- multiple Schedule 1 Canadian banks on a multi-billion-dollar financial processing services outsourcing;
- multiple public sector entities with respect to the replacement of shared IT systems and the outsourcing of application management services and IT infrastructure services;
- a public sector body on its participation in a data sharing network for digital identity verification using blockchain-based technology;
- a government on an outcomes-based services agreement for call centre services;
- a multinational energy company on an Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) procurement and implementation project for its regulated utilities in Canada and the United States;
- a regional transportation agency in the competitive procurement and implementation of a new ERP system to replace its legacy system;
- a Canadian real estate company in negotiating several software license and cloud services agreements for a new ERP system;
- a Canadian bank on a complex project to implement network and communications technology upgrades for over 1,000 branches across Canada;
- a credit union on the outsourcing of managed cybersecurity services;
- a provincial government on a $1-billion telecommunications services agreement;
- a Canadian bank on a $1.25-billion telecommunications services agreement;
- a Canadian bank on its outsourcing of mortgage underwriting fulfillment and funding services and implementation of related point of sale platforms, networks and integrations;
- a public sector entity on the public procurement and implementation of a cloud-based e-commerce platform for the sale of regulated products;
- a government with respect to its procurement and implementation of a modern SaaS treasury management system to replace its end-of-life mainframe application;
- a government on the procurement of a cloud-based digital education assessment system;
- a government on a billion-dollar outsourcing of real property (including facilities management) services covering over 1,500 owned, leased and managed properties in a province;
- a credit union with respect to a credit card payment processing agreement;
- a government with respect to the procurement and implementation of a cloud-based public reservation system; and
- a national Canadian engineering services company with respect to a data breach incident.
David frequently speaks at industry and legal conferences and writes publications on topics such as commercial drafting, outsourcings, IT projects, artificial intelligence, cloud computing, data centres, cybersecurity, big data, Internet of Things (IoT), identity management, OSFI B-10, B-13 and E-23 Guidelines compliance, open banking, contracting for IT through resellers, procurement law, and start-up issues. He is a former director of the Canadian Technology Law Association.
David received a B.Comm. (Honours with Distinction) from the University of Manitoba in 1997 and his LLB from the University of British Columbia in 2001. He was called to the British Columbia bar in 2002.
